revision.text:
{{External links|date=September 2018}}
The term '''aggravated felony''' was created by the [[United States Congress]] as part of the [[Immigration and Nationality Act]] (INA) to define a special category of [[crime|criminal offenses]].<ref name=a-f-1988/><ref name=a-f-1996/> The INA says that some [[alien (law)#United States|aliens]] "convicted of an aggravated felony shall be considered to have been convicted of a [[particularly serious crime]]."<ref name="particularly serious crime"/> Every "legal immigrant," including a "[[national of the United States|national]] but not a citizen of the United States,"<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States"/> who has been convicted of any aggravated felony is statutorily barred from obtaining [[citizenship of the United States]].<ref name=1101(a)(19)/><ref name=1101(f)(8)/><ref name=1427(d)-(e)/><ref name="a-f-1996"/><ref name=OPA/><ref name=OPA2/> Other than a [[refugee]],<ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/><ref name=refugee/> every alien who has been convicted of any aggravated felony is statutorily barred from receiving a [[visa policy of the United States|visa]] or being admitted to the United States, unless its "term of [[imprisonment]] was completed within the previous 15 years."<ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name="aliens previously removed">{{uscsub|8|1182|a|9|A|iii}} ("Clauses (i) and (ii) '''''shall not apply''''' to an alien seeking admission within a period if, prior to the date of the alien's reembarkation at a place outside the United States or attempt to be admitted from foreign contiguous territory, '''''the Attorney General has consented''''' to the alien's reapplying for admission.") (emphasis added)</ref><ref name="statutory interpretation"/><ref name="reasonable interpretation"/><ref name="notwithstanding clause"/><ref name="Kennedy v. Mendoza-Martinez"/>

When the aggravated felony was introduced in 1988, as a response to heightened concerns about drug abuse, it encompassed only [[murder]] and [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|felony]] [[wikt:trafficking#English|trafficking]] in drugs and/or [[firearm]]s (but not [[long gun|long]] [[shotgun]]s, [[long gun|long]] [[rifle]]s, and/or [[ammunition]] of such legal weapons).<ref name=a-f-1988/><ref>{{uscsub|18|921|a|17}}; {{usc|26|5845}}; see also 18 [[Pennsylvania Consolidated Statutes|Pa. Cons. Stat.]] [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/18/00.061.002.000..HTM § 6102]; {{usc|18|927}} ("Effect on State law").</ref> Every conviction covered by the aggravated felony was manifestly a [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|crime punishable by imprisonment for a term exceeding one year]].<ref name=a-f-1988/> The 1996 enactment of the [[Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996|Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act]] (AEDPA) and the [[Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996|Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act]] (IIRIRA) tremendously expanded the aggravated felony definition by adding a great many more criminal convictions.<ref name="Othi v. Holder"/> The chart at the bottom lists all the [[aggravated felony#List of aggravated felonies|aggravated felonies]].

==Background==
{{Further|Immigration and Nationality Act of 1952}}
[[File:Lennon's Green Card.jpg|thumb|A 1976 [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|permanent resident card]], issued by the former [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]] (INS), stating the following: "This is to certify that [[John Lennon|[John Lennon]]] has been duly registered according to the [[Immigration and Nationality Act|law]] and was admitted to the United States as an [[wikt:immigrant#English|immigrant]]...."<ref name=immigrant/>]]
The INA states that "[t]he term '[[alien (law)#United States|alien]]' means any person not a [[citizenship of the United States|citizen]] '''''or''''' [[national of the United States]]."<ref name=alien>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|3}} (emphasis added); see also {{uscsub|8|1101|a|22}} ("The term '[[national of the United States]]' means (A) a [[citizenship of the United States|citizen of the United States]], '''''or (B) a person who, though not a citizen of the United States, owes permanent allegiance to the United States'''''.") (emphasis added); {{uscsub|8|1101|a|31}} ("The term '[[wikt:permanent|permanent]]' means a relationship of continuing or lasting nature, as distinguished from temporary, but a relationship may be permanent even though it is one that may be dissolved eventually at the instance either of the United States or of the individual, in accordance with law."); {{uscsub|8|1101|a|33}} ("The term '[[residence]]' means the place of general [[dwelling|abode]]; the place of general abode of a person means his principal, actual [[dwelling]] place in fact, without regard to intent."); [[Black's Law Dictionary]] at p.87 (9th ed., 2009) (defining the term "permanent allegiance" as "[t]he lasting [[allegiance]] owed to [the United States] by its citizens '''''or''''' [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|[permanent resident]s]].") (emphasis added); ''Ricketts v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20180730056 897 F.3d 491], 493-94 n.3 (3d Cir. 2018) ("[[Citizenship]] and [[nationality]] are not [[synonym|synonymous]]."); ''[[Jennings v. Rodriguez]]'', 138 S.Ct. 830, 855-56 (2018) ([[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Clarence Thomas|Thomas]] concurring) ("The term 'or' is almost always [[logical disjunction|disjunctive]], that is, the [phrase]s it connects are to be given separate meanings."); ''Chalmers v. Shalala'', [https://casetext.com/case/chalmers-v-shalala#p755 23 F.3d 752], 755 (3d Cir. 1994) (same).</ref> The terms "inadmissible aliens" and "deportable aliens" are [[synonym|synonymous]],<ref name=removable>{{uscsub|8|1229a|e|2}} ("The term 'removable' means—(A) in the case of an alien not admitted to the United States, that the alien is inadmissible under section 1182 of this title, or (B) in the case of an alien admitted to the United States, that the alien is deportable under section 1227 of this title."); ''Galindo v. Sessions'', 897 F.3d 894, ___, [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca7/17-1253/17-1253-2018-07-31.html No. 17-1253], p.4-5 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|7th Cir.]] July 31, 2018); ''Tima v. Attorney General of the U.S.'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [http://www2.ca3.uscourts.gov/opinarch/164199p.pdf No. 16-4199], p.11 (3d Cir. Sept. 6, 2018) ("Section 1227 defines '[d]eportable aliens,' a [[synonym]] for removable aliens.... So § 1227(a)(1) [[wikt:piggyback#English|piggybacks]] on § 1182(a) by treating grounds of inadmissibility as grounds for removal as well.").</ref> which mainly refer to the INA violators among the 75 million [[foreign national#In the United States|foreign nationals]] who are admitted each year as [[visa policy of the United States|guests]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Destination USA: 75 million international guests visited in 2014 |url=https://share.america.gov/75-million-tourists-visited-us-2014/ |publisher=share.america.gov |accessdate=2018-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=International Visitation to the United States: A Statistical Summary of U.S. Visitation |url=https://travel.trade.gov/outreachpages/download_data_table/2015_Visitation_Report.pdf |year=2015 |pages=2 |publisher=[[United States Department of Commerce|U.S. Department of Commerce]] |accessdate=2018-09-30}}</ref> the 12 million or so [[illegal immigrant population of the United States|illegal aliens]],<ref name="section 1365(b)">{{uscsub|8|1365|b}} ("An illegal alien ... is any alien ... who is in the United States unlawfully....").</ref> and the INA violators among the 400,000 foreign nationals who possess the [[temporary protected status]] (TPS).<ref name=TPS>{{uscsub|8|1254a|f}} ("Benefits and status during period of temporary protected status"); ''Saliba v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/saliba-v-attorney-gen-of-us 828 F.3d 182] (3d Cir. 2016); see also {{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/la-na-tps-revoked-20180720-story.html |title=The Trump administration wants more than 400,000 people to leave the U.S. Here's who they are and why |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |editor=Melissa Etehad |date=July 19, 2018 |accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>

A legal immigrant, particularly one who was admitted as a [[refugee]] pursuant to 8 U.S.C. § 1157(c), can either be an alien or a [[national of the United States]] ([[Americans|American]]), which requires a case-by-case analysis and depends mainly on the number of continuous years he or she has spent in the United States as a [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|lawful permanent resident]] (LPR).<ref name="U.S. nationality claim"/><ref name=American/><ref name=Stanton/><ref name=Sakuma/><ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/>

===Firm resettlement of refugees in the United States===
{{Further|Refugee Act|Lawful permanent residents (United States)}}
[[President of the United States|U.S. Presidents]] and the U.S. Congress have expressly favored some "legal immigrants"<ref name="anti-discrimination"/> because the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]] had admitted them to the United States as [[refugee]]s, i.e., people who experienced [[genocide]]s in the past and have no safe country of [[permanent residency|permanent residence]] other than the United States.<ref name="Matter of H-N-">''Matter of H-N-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3414.pdf 22 I&N Dec. 1039], 1040-45 ([[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] 1999) ([[en banc]]) (case of a female [[Cambodian Americans|Cambodian-American]] who was convicted of a [[particularly serious crime]] but "the [[Immigration Judge (United States)|Immigration Judge]] found [her] eligible for a [[waiver of inadmissibility (United States)|waiver of inadmissibility]], as well as for [[adjustment of status]], and he granted her this relief from removal."); ''Matter of Jean'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3472.pdf 23 I&N Dec. 373], 381 ([[United States Attorney General|A.G.]] 2002) ("Aliens, like the respondent, who have been admitted (or conditionally admitted) into the United States as [[refugee]]s can seek an adjustment of status only under INA § 209."); INA § 209(c), {{uscsub|8|1159|c}} ("The provisions of paragraphs (4), (5), and (7)(A) of section 1182(a) of [[title 8 of the United States Code|this title]] <u>shall not be applicable</u> to any alien seeking adjustment of status under [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1159 this section], and the [[United States Secretary of Homeland Security|Secretary of Homeland Security]] or the [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] may waive any other provision of [section 1182] ... with respect to such an alien for <u>[[wikt:humanitarian#English|humanitarian]] purposes, to assure [[family]] unity, '''''or''''' when it is otherwise in the [[public interest]]</u>.") (emphasis added); ''Nguyen v. Chertoff'', [https://casetext.com/case/nguyen-v-chertoff#p110 501 F.3d 107], 109-10 (2d Cir. 2007) (petition granted of a [[Vietnamese Americans|Vietnamese-American]] convicted of a [[particularly serious crime]]); ''[[City of Cleburne v. Cleburne Living Center, Inc.]]'', [http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep473/usrep473432/usrep473432.pdf 473 U.S. 432], 439 (1985) ("The [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] commands that ... all persons similarly situated should be treated alike.").</ref><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-">''Matter of J-H-J-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/pages/attachments/2015/05/12/3836_0.pdf 26 I&N Dec. 563] ([[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] 2015) (collecting court cases) ("An alien who [[adjustment of status|adjusted status]] in the United States, and who '''has not entered''' as a [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|lawful permanent resident]], is not barred from establishing eligibility for a [[waiver of inadmissibility (United States)|waiver of inadmissibility]] under section 212(h) of the Immigration and Nationality Act, {{uscsub|8|1182|h}} (2012), as a result of an aggravated felony conviction.") (emphasis added); see also ''De Leon v. Lynch'', [https://casetext.com/case/cristian-eduardo-obregon-de-leon-v-lynch#p1232 808 F.3d 1224], 1232 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit|10th Cir.]] 2015) ("[Petitioner] next claims that even if he is removable, he should nevertheless have been afforded the opportunity to apply for a waiver under {{uscsub|8|1182|h}}. Under controlling precedent from our court and the [[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]]'s recent decision in ''Matter of J–H–J–'', '''he is correct'''.") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/><ref name=McCormick>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/society/article/2160861/strangers-their-homeland-khmerican-cambodians-trump-deported |title=Strangers in their homeland: the Khmerican Cambodians Trump deported |first=Andrew |last=McCormick |date=August 25, 2017 |accessdate=2018-10-01 |publisher=[[South China Morning Post]] (SCMP)}}</ref> Removing such protected people from the United States constitutes a [[particularly serious crime|grave international crime]],<ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name="war crimes"/><ref name=CAT/><ref name="CQ Press"/><ref name="anti-discrimination"/> especially if they qualify as [[Americans]] or have physically and continuously resided in the United States for at least 10 years without committing (in those 10 years) any offense that triggers removability.<ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/><ref name=American/><ref name="U.S. nationality claim"/><ref name=Stanton>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlive.com/news/ann-arbor/index.ssf/2018/05/after_facing_deportation_ann_a.html |title=Michigan father of 4 was nearly deported; now he's a U.S. citizen |date=May 11, 2018 |accessdate=2018-10-22 |publisher=www.mlive.com |last=Stanton |first=Ryan}}</ref><ref name=Sakuma>{{cite web |title=Lawsuit says ICE attorney forged document to deport immigrant man |url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/lawsuit-claims-ice-attorney-forged-document-deport-immigrant-man |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |date=October 24, 2014 |accessdate=2018-10-22 |last=Sakuma |first=Amanda}}</ref><ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/><ref name="burden of proof"/>

In ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 459|Landon v. Plasencia]]'', [https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/459/21/ 459 U.S. 21], 32 (1982), the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] reminded all U.S. immigration officials that "once an alien gains admission to our country and begins to develop the ties that go with [[permanent residency|permanent residence]], his [[United States Constitution|constitutional]] status changes accordingly." That opinion was issued after Congress and the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]] ''[[third country resettlement|firmly resettled]]'' in the United States thousands of refugee families from [[totalitarianism|totalitarian states]], such as [[Deportation of Afghan refugees from the United States|Afghanistan]], [[Deportation of Cambodian refugees from the United States|Cambodia]], [[Cuba]], [[Laos]], [[Vietnam]], etc.<ref name=refugee>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|42}} ("The term 'refugee' means (A) '''''any person who''''' is outside any country of such person's nationality or, in the case of a person having no nationality, '''''is outside any country in which such person last habitually resided''''', and who is unable ... to return to, and is unable ... to avail himself ... of the protection of, that country because of [[persecution]] ... on account of race, religion, nationality, membership in a [[particular social group]], or political opinion....") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="Matter of Izatula">''Matter of Izatula'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2012/08/14/3127.pdf 20 I&N Dec. 149], 154 (BIA 1990) ("Afghanistan is a [[totalitarianism|totalitarian state]] under the control of the [[People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan|[People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan]]], which is kept in power by the [[Soviet Union]].").</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/cambodia-khmer-rouge-guilty-genocide-court-rules-181116043953706.html |title=Cambodia: Khmer Rouge leaders guilty of genocide, court rules |date=November 16, 2018 |accessdate=2018-11-19 |publisher=Al Jazeera |quote=Verdict after years of trial is first time any Khmer Rouge leaders were found guilty of genocide for 1975-79 terror.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2017-11-09/some-vietnamese-immigrants-were-protected-deportation-trump-administration-may-be |title=Some Vietnamese immigrants were protected from deportation, but the Trump administration may be changing that policy |first=Marnette |last=Federis |date=March 3, 2018 |accessdate=September 25, 2018 |publisher=[[Public Radio International]] (PRI)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/mar/03/vietnamese-refugees-immigration-us-detention |title=Detained and divided: how the US turned on Vietnamese refugees |first=Sam |last=Levin |date=November 10, 2017 |accessdate=September 25, 2018 |publisher=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> As [[United Nations|U.N.]]-recognized refugees, these people permanently lost their homes, farms, businesses, properties, livelihood, relatives, etc. They also lost their former nationalities after obtaining [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|permanent resident cards]] (green cards) of the United States, and then gradually became [[Americans]].

===Expansion of the definition of "nationals but not citizens of the United States"===
{{Further|Americans|United States nationality law}}
In 1986, less than a year before the [[United Nations Convention against Torture]] (CAT) became effective, Congress expressly and intentionally expanded the definition of "[[national of the United States|nationals]] but not [[citizenship of the United States|citizens of the United States]]" by adding paragraph (4) to 8 U.S.C. § 1408, which reads as follows:{{Quote|Unless otherwise provided in section [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1401 1401] of this title, the following ''shall'' be '''''nationals, but not citizens, of the United States''''' at birth: .... (4) '''''A person''''' born outside the United States '''''and''''' its [[territories of the United States|outlying possessions]] of parents one of whom is an [[alien (law)#United States|alien]], and the other a '''''national, but not a citizen, of the United States''''' who, prior to the birth of such person, was physically present in the '''''United States''''' or its outlying possessions for a period or periods <u>totaling not less than seven years in any continuous period of ten years</u>—(A) '''''during which the [[national of the United States|national]] [[parent]] was not outside the United States''''' or its outlying possessions '''''for a continuous period of more than one year''''', and (B) at least five years of which were after attaining the age of fourteen years.<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States">{{USC|8|1408}} (emphasis added); see also {{USC|8|1436}} ("Nationals but not citizens....").</ref><ref name="Alabama v. Bozeman">''[[Alabama v. Bozeman]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/alabama-v-bozeman#p153 533 U.S. 146, 153] (2001) ("The word 'shall' is ordinarily the language of command.") (internal quotation marks omitted).</ref>}}

The natural reading of § 1408(4) demonstrates that it was not exclusively written for the 55,000 [[American Samoa]]ns but for all people who statutorily and manifestly qualify as "nationals but not citizens of the United States."<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States"/><ref>{{uscsub|8|1427|b}} (explaining that [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|lawful permanent residents]] may lawfully remain outside the United States for up to one year (or even longer) in certain situations).</ref><ref name="reasonable interpretation"/> This means that any person who can show by a [[burden of proof (law)#Preponderance of the evidence|preponderance of the evidence]] that he or she meets (or at any time has met) the requirements of 8 U.S.C. §§ 1408(4), 1427, 1429, 1436, and/or 1445, is plainly and unambiguously an [[Americans|American]].<ref name=American/><ref name="U.S. nationality claim">''Ricketts v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20180730056 897 F.3d 491] (3d Cir. 2018) ("When an alien faces removal under the Immigration and Nationality Act, one potential defense is that the alien is not an alien at all but is actually a [[national of the United States]]."); ''Mohammadi v. Islamic Republic of Iran'', [https://casetext.com/case/mohammadi-v-islamic-republic-of-iran-1#p15 782 F.3d 9], 15 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Cir.]] 2015) ("The sole such statutory provision that presently confers United States nationality upon non-citizens is {{usc|8|1408}}."); ''Matter of Navas-Acosta'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3489.pdf 23 I&N Dec. 586], 587 (BIA 2003) ("If Congress had intended nationality to attach at some point before the [[naturalization]] process is complete, we believe it would have said so."); {{USC|8|1436}} ("A person not a citizen who owes [[wikt:permanent#English|permanent]] [[allegiance]] to the United States, and who is otherwise qualified, may, if he becomes a [[residency (domicile)|resident]] of any [[U.S. state|State]], be [[naturalization|naturalized]] upon compliance with the applicable requirements of [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/chapter-12/subchapter-III this subchapter]...."); ''Saliba v. Att’y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/saliba-v-attorney-gen-of-us#p189 828 F.3d 182], 189 (3d Cir. 2016) ("Significantly, an applicant for naturalization has the burden of proving 'by a [[burden of proof (law)#Preponderance of the evidence|preponderance of the evidence]] that he or she meets all of the requirements for naturalization.'"); {{uscsub|8|1101|a|23}} ("The term 'naturalization' means the conferring of [United States nationality] upon a person after birth, '''''by any means whatsoever'''''.") (emphasis added); see also ''In re Petition of Haniatakis'', [https://casetext.com/case/in-re-petition-of-haniatakis 376 F.2d 728] (3d Cir. 1967); ''In re Sotos' Petition'', [https://casetext.com/case/in-re-sotos-petition 221 F. Supp. 145] ([[United States District Court for the Western District of Pennsylvania|W.D. Pa.]] 1963).</ref><ref name=Stanton/><ref name=Sakuma/><ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/> Such person must never be labelled or treated as an alien. "Deprivation of [[nationality|[nationality]]]—particularly [[United States nationality law|American [nationality]]], which is one of the most valuable rights in the world today—has grave practical consequences."<ref name="Kennedy v. Mendoza-Martinez">''[[Kennedy v. Mendoza-Martinez]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/kennedy-v-mendoza-martinez#p160 372 U.S. 144], 160 (1963) (citation and internal quotation marks omitted); see also ''[[Arizona v. United States]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/arizona-v-united-states-7#p395 567 U.S. 387], 395 (2012) ("Perceived mistreatment of aliens in the United States may lead to harmful [[wikt:reciprocal#English|reciprocal]] treatment of American citizens abroad."); {{cite web|title=Certificates of Non Citizen Nationality |url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/legal/travel-legal-considerations/us-citizenship/Certificates-Non-Citizen-Nationality.html |work=[[Bureau of Consular Affairs]] |date=|publisher=[[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]] |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name="war crimes"/><ref name=CAT/><ref name="CQ Press"/><ref name=anti-discrimination/><ref name=LexisNexis>{{cite web |title=No Apologies, But Feds Pay $350K to Deported American Citizen |url=https://www.lexisnexis.com/LegalNewsRoom/immigration/b/newsheadlines/posts/no-apologies-but-feds-pay-350k-to-deported-american-citizen |last=Stevens |first=Jacqueline |publisher=[[LexisNexis]] |date=June 2, 2015 |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref><ref name=Document171>{{cite web |title=Peter Guzman and Maria Carbajal, v. United States, CV08-01327 GHK (SSx) |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.cacd.409690.171.0.pdf |page=3 |work=[[United States District Court for the Central District of California|U.S. District Court for the Central District of California]] (CDCA) |publisher=www.courtlistener.com |date=June 7, 2010 |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref> This legal finding "is consistent with one of the most basic [[statutory interpretation#Canons|interpretive canons]], that a [[statutory law|statute]] should be construed so that effect is given to all its provisions, so that no part will be inoperative or superfluous, void or insignificant."<ref name="statutory interpretation">''[[Rubin v. Islamic Republic of Iran]]'', 583 U.S. ___ (2018) ([https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/16-534_6jfm.pdf Slip Opinion at 10]) (internal quotation marks and brackets omitted); see also ''Matter of Song'', [https://www.justice.gov/eoir/page/file/1112411/download 27 I&N Dec. 488], 492 (BIA 2018) ("Because the language of both the [[Title 8 of the United States Code|statute]] and the [[Title 8 of the Code of Federal Regulations|regulations]] is plain and unambiguous, we are bound to follow it."); ''Matter of Figueroa'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3727.pdf 25 I&N Dec. 596], 598 (BIA 2011) ("When interpreting [[Title 8 of the United States Code|statutes]] and [[Title 8 of the Code of Federal Regulations|regulations]], we look first to the plain meaning of the language and are required to give effect to unambiguously expressed intent. [[Executive Office for Immigration Review|Executive]] intent is presumed to be expressed by the ordinary meaning of the words used. We also construe a statute or regulation to give effect to all of its provisions.") (citations omitted); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 540|Lamie v. United States Trustee]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/lamie-v-us-trustee#p534 540 U.S. 526], 534 (2004); ''[[TRW Inc. v. Andrews]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/trw-inc-v-andrews#p31 534 U.S. 19], 31 (2001) ("It is a [[wikt:cardinal#English|cardinal]] [[principle]] of [[statutory interpretation|statutory construction]] that a [[statutory law|statute]] ought, upon the whole, to be so construed that, if it can be prevented, no clause, sentence, or word shall be superfluous, void, or insignificant.") (internal quotation marks omitted); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 348|United States v. Menasche]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-menasche#p538 348 U.S. 528], 538-539 (1955) ("It is our duty to give effect, if possible, to every clause and word of a [[statutory law|statute]]." (internal quotation marks omitted); ''[[NLRB v. Jones & Laughlin Steel Corp.]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/labor-board-v-laughlin#p30 301 U.S. 1], 30 (1937) ("The cardinal principle of statutory construction is to save and not to destroy. We have repeatedly held that as between two possible interpretations of a statute, by one of which it would be unconstitutional and by the other valid, our plain duty is to adopt that which will save the act. Even to avoid a serious doubt the rule is the same.").</ref>

==Consequences of an aggravated felony conviction==
[[File:2017-us-green-card-specimen.png|thumb|Sample of a [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|permanent resident card]] (green card), which lawfully permits its holder to live and work in the [[United States]] similar to that of all other [[Americans]]. Before any legal immigrant is naturalized as a U.S. citizen, he or she must be a green card holder for at least 5 years and satisfy all other INA's naturalization requirements. Many green card holders are actually Americans without them knowing, and are thus not removable from the United States.<ref name=Lee/><ref name=Stanton/><ref name=Sakuma/><ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name=OPA2/>]]
In 1988, Congress introduced the term "aggravated felony" by defining it under 8 U.S.C. § 1101(a).<ref name=a-f-1988>{{cite web |url=https://www.gpo.gov/ |title=Subtitle J—Provisions Relating to the Deportation of Aliens Who Commit Aggravated Felonies, Pub. L. 100-690, 102 Stat. 4469-79, § 7342 |date=November 18, 1988 |accessdate=July 22, 2018|pages=289–90|quote=Section 101(a) (8 U.S.C. 1101(a)) is amended by adding at the end thereof the following new paragraph: '(43) The term 'aggravated felony' means [[murder]], any drug trafficking crime '''''as defined in''''' [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/924#c_2 section 924(c)(2) of title 18, United States Code], or any illicit trafficking in any firearms or destructive devices <u>as defined in [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/921 section 921</u> of such title], or any attempt or conspiracy to commit any such act, committed within the United States.'|work=U.S. Congress}}</ref> The definition of the term gradually expanded over the years, and applies (for [[Form N-400|U.S. citizenship]] purposes) to offenses that were committed at any time in the past.<ref name="Requirements of naturalization">See generally {{USC|8|1427}} ("Requirements of naturalization"); see also
*{{cite web |url=https://www.uscis.gov/us-citizenship/citizenship-through-naturalization/path-us-citizenship |title=Path to U.S. Citizenship |date=January 22, 2013 |accessdate=2018-09-30 |publisher=[[United States Citizenship and Immigration Services]] (USCIS)}} 
*{{cite web |url=https://www.usa.gov/become-us-citizen |title=How to Apply for U.S. Citizenship |date=September 4, 2018 |accessdate=2018-09-30 |publisher=www.usa.gov}}</ref><ref name=1101(f)(8)>{{uscsub|8|1101|f|8}} ("No person shall be regarded as, or found to be, a person of [[good moral character]] who, during the period for which good moral character is required to be established is, or was ... (8) ''one who at any time has been convicted of an aggravated felony'' (as defined in subsection (a)(43))....") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="Al-Sharif v. USCIS">''Al-Sharif v. United States Citizenship and Immigration Services'', [https://casetext.com/case/al-sharif-v-us-citizenship-immigration-servs-2 734 F.3d 207] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit|3d Cir.]] 2013) ([[en banc]]) (case involving a non-deportable aggravated felon); see also ''Mobin v. Taylor'', [https://casetext.com/case/mobin-v-taylor 598 F.Supp.2d 777] ([[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia|E.D. Va.]] 2009) (same).</ref> In February 1995, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] issued a directive in which he expressly stated the following: {{Quote|Our efforts to combat [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]] <u>must not violate the [[privacy]] and [[civil and political rights|civil rights]] of '''''legal immigrants''''' and U.S. citizens</u>. Therefore, I direct the Attorney General, the [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary of Health and Human Services]], the Chair of the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]], and other relevant [[Executive Office for Immigration Review|Administration officials]] <u>to vigorously protect our citizens and '''''legal immigrants''''' from immigration-related instances of [[discrimination]] and [[harassment]]</u>. All illegal immigration enforcement measures ''shall'' be taken with due regard for the basic [[human rights in the United States|human rights]] of individuals and in accordance with our obligations under applicable [[treaty|international agreements]]. (emphasis added).<ref name=anti-discrimination>{{cite web |title=60 FR 7885: ANTI-DISCRIMINATION |url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-1995-02-10/pdf/95-3554.pdf |pages=7888 |date=February 10, 1995 |accessdate=July 16, 2018|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|U.S. Government Publishing Office]]}} See also ''Zuniga-Perez v. Sessions'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca2/17-996/17-996-2018-07-25.html No. 17-996], p.11 (2d Cir. July 25, 2018) ("The [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] protects both '''citizens''' and '''non‐citizens'''.") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="Alabama v. Bozeman"/>}}

Despite what President Clinton said in the above directive, some [[qualified immunity|plainly incompetent]] [[immigration officer]]s waged an unlawful war against those who were not U.S. citizens. They began this by [[arrest]]ing and deporting long-settled legal immigrants (i.e., potential [[Americans]]).<ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/><ref name=immigrant/> Many of these legal immigrants were ''[[third country resettlement|firmly resettled]]'' and non-deportable [[refugee]]s,<ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/> who statutorily qualified as Americans after continuously residing in the United States for at least 10 years without committing any offense that triggers removability.<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States"/><ref name="section 1101(a)(13)(C)(v)">{{uscsub|8|1101|a|13|C|v}} (stating that an LPR, especially a wrongfully-deported LPR, is permitted to reenter the United States by any means whatsoever, including with a grant of "relief under section [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1182#h 1182(h)] '''''or''''' [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1229b#a 1229b(a)] of [[title 8 of the United States Code|this title]]....") (emphasis added); accord ''United States v. Aguilera-Rios'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-aguilera-rios-2#p629 769 F.3d 626], 628-29 (9th Cir. 2014) ("[Petitioner] was convicted of a California firearms offense, removed from the United States on the basis of that conviction, and, when he returned to the country, tried and convicted of illegal reentry under {{USC|8|1326}}. He contends that his prior removal order was [[wikt:invalid#English|invalid]] because his conviction ... was not a categorical match for the Immigration and Nationality Act's ('INA') firearms offense. We agree that he was not originally removable as charged, and so could not be convicted of illegal reentry."); see also ''Matter of Campos-Torres'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3428.pdf 22 I&N Dec. 1289] (BIA 2000) (en banc) (A firearms offense that renders an alien removable under section 237(a)(2)(C) of the Act, {{uscsub|8|1227|a|2|C}} (Supp. II 1996), is not one 'referred to in section 212(a)(2)' and thus does not stop the further accrual of continuous residence or continuous physical presence for purposes of establishing eligibility for cancellation of removal."); ''[[Vartelas v. Holder]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/vartelas-v-holder-10#p262 566 U.S. 257], 262 (2012).</ref> This appears to be the reason why the permanent resident card (green card) is valid for 10 years. It was expected that all refugees in the United States would obtain [[citizenship of the United States|U.S. citizenship]] within 10 years from the date of their first lawful entry,<ref name=admission>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|13|A}} ("The terms 'admission' and 'admitted' mean, with respect to an alien, the '''''lawful entry''''' of the alien into the United States after [[inspection]] and [[authorization]] by an [[immigration officer]].") (emphasis added); ''Matter of D-K-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3747.pdf 25 I&N Dec. 761], 765-66 (BIA 2012).</ref><ref name="Requirements of naturalization"/> but if that was unachievable then they would statutorily become "nationals but not citizens of the United States" after such continuous 10 years successfully elapse.<ref name="reasonable interpretation">''[[Robinson v. Shell Oil Co.]]'', 519 U.S. 337, 341 (1997) ("The plainness or ambiguity of statutory language is determined by reference to the language itself, the specific context in which that language is used, and the broader context of the statute as a whole."); see also ''Matter of Dougless'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3792_final.pdf 26 I&N Dec. 197], 199 (BIA 2013) ("The [Supreme] Court  has  also emphasized that the ''[[Chevron U.S.A., Inc. v. Natural Resources Defense Council, Inc.|Chevron]]'' principle of deference must be applied to an agency’s interpretation of ambiguous statutory provisions, even where a court has previously issued a contrary decision and believes that its construction is the better one, provided that the agency's interpretation is reasonable.").</ref> They obviously owe [[wikt:permanent#English|permanent]] [[allegiance]] solely to the government of the United States,<ref name=immigrant>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|20}} ("The term '[[lawful permanent residents (United States)|lawfully admitted for permanent residence]]' means the status of having been lawfully [[wikt:accord#English|accorded]] the [[wikt:privilege#English|privilege]] of residing [[wikt:permanently#English|permanently]] in the United States as an [[wikt:immigrant#English|immigrant]] ...."); see also {{uscsub|8|1101|a|15}} (defining the term "immigrant").</ref><ref name=alien/> and that makes them nothing but [[Americans]]. Anything to the contrary manifestly constitutes deprivation of [[human rights in the United States|their legal rights]].<ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name="war crimes"/><ref name=CAT/><ref name="CQ Press"/><ref name=anti-discrimination/><ref name="Kennedy v. Mendoza-Martinez"/>

An aggravated felony conviction affects both aliens and "nationals but not citizens of the United States."<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States"/> The INA makes clear that any such person who at any time has been convicted of any aggravated felony, whether the aggravated felony was committed inside or outside the United States, is "[[wikt:debar#English|debarred]] from becoming a [[citizenship of the United States|citizen of the United States]]."<ref name=1101(a)(19)>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|19}}</ref><ref name=1101(f)(8)/><ref name=1427(d)-(e)>{{cite web |title=8 U.S.C. § 1427(d)-(e) |url= https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1427#e |publisher=Cornell Law School |work= U.S. Congress |accessdate=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref name=OPA>{{cite news|title=Justice Department Seeks to Revoke Citizenship of Convicted Felons Who Conspired to Defraud U.S. Export-Import Bank of More Than $24 Million |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-seeks-revoke-citizenship-convicted-felons-who-conspired-defraud-us-export |date=May 8, 2018 |publisher=U.S. Dept. of Justice (DOJ) |work=Office of Public Affairs |accessdate=2018-10-16}}</ref><ref name=OPA2>{{cite news|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/justice-department-secures-denaturalization-guardian-convicted-sexual-abuse-minor |title=Justice Department Secures Denaturalization of Guardian Convicted of Sexual Abuse of A Minor|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Justice (DOJ) |work=Office of Public Affairs |accessdate=2018-10-16 |date=August 13, 2018 |quote=Under our laws, United States citizenship is conferred on those who demonstrate honesty and integrity, who respect our laws, and who can demonstrate the [[good moral character|moral character]] necessary to be a positive and cultivating member of American society....}}</ref><ref name="burden of proof"/> However, unlike a "national but not a citizen of the United States," an alien convicted of any aggravated felony is removable from the United States as an aggravated felon, unless its "term of [[imprisonment]] was completed within the previous 15 years."<ref name=a-f-1996/><ref name="statutory interpretation"/><ref name="reasonable interpretation"/> In other words, such alien cannot:
* be admitted to the United States prior to being granted a [[waiver of inadmissibility (United States)|waiver of inadmissibility]] or [[cancellation of removal]] by any authorized U.S. immigration official,<ref name="section 1101(a)(13)(C)(v)"/><ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/> or "a full and unconditional [[Pardon#United States|pardon]] by the [[President of the United States]] or by the [[Governor (United States)|Governor]] of any of the several [[U.S. state|States]]."<ref>{{uscsub|8|1227|a|2|A|vi}}</ref>
* apply for [[adjustment of status]] unless he or she was previously admitted to the United States as a [[refugee]].<ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/>
* have his or her [[removal proceedings]] [[cancellation of removal|terminated]] without an official order issued by any immigration official,<ref name="Matter of S-O-G- & F-D-B-"/> or an [[injunction]] issued by any [[United States federal judge|federal judge]].<ref name="injunctive relief"/><ref name=American/><ref name="injunctive relief 2"/>
* receive [[asylum in the United States]] unless he or she was previously admitted to the United States as a refugee,<ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/> or his or her aggravated felony was shown not to be a [[particularly serious crime]].<ref name="particularly serious crime">{{uscsub|8|1158|b|2|B|i}}; see also ''Matter of G-G-S-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3806.pdf 26 I&N Dec. 339], 347 n.6 ([[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] 2014).</ref> An alien convicted of a [[particularly serious crime]] may still receive asylum, so long as he or she is not "a danger to the community of the United States,"<ref>{{uscsub|8|1158|b|2|A|ii}} ("Paragraph (1) shall not apply to an alien if the Attorney General determines that— ... (ii) '''''the alien''''', having been convicted by a final judgment of a particularly serious crime, '''''constitutes a danger to the community of the United States'''''").</ref> or at minimum deferral of removal under the [[United Nations Convention against Torture|CAT]].<ref name="deferral of removal">''Anwari v. Attorney General of the U.S.'', [http://www2.ca3.uscourts.gov/opinarch/181505np.pdf Nos. 18-1505 & 18-2291], p.6 (3rd Cir. Nov. 6, 2018) ("To qualify for deferral of removal under the [[United Nations Convention against Torture|CAT]], an applicant must show that he is 'more likely than not' to be tortured. {{uscfr|8|1208.16}}(c)(2). [[Torture]] is defined as any act by which severe pain or suffering, whether physical or mental, is intentionally inflicted on a person ... when such pain or suffering is inflicted by or at the instigation of or with the consent or acquiescence of a public official or other person acting in an official capacity.") (internal quotation marks omitted); see also ''Matter of Y-L-, A-G- & R-S-R-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3464.pdf 23 I&N Dec. 270], 279 (A.G. 2002) ("Although the respondents are statutorily ineligible for withholding of removal by virtue of their convictions for '[[particularly serious crimes]],' the regulations implementing the [[United Nations Convention against Torture|Convention Against Torture]] allow them to obtain a deferral of removal notwithstanding the prior criminal offenses if they can establish that they are 'entitled to protection' under the Convention."); {{uscsub|8|1252|a|4}} ("Claims under the United Nations Convention").</ref> It must be added that granting the CAT is not a discretionary action but statutory and mandatory.<ref name="section 1252(a)(2)(B)(ii)">{{uscsub|8|1252|a|2|B|ii}} (stating that "the authority for which is ''specified'' under this subchapter to be in the ''[[discretion]]'' of the Attorney General or the Secretary of Homeland Security, '''''other than the granting of relief under section 1158(a)'''''....").</ref><ref name="deferral of removal"/>

===Challenging an aggravated felony charge===
{{Further|Removal proceedings|Expedited removal}}
An "[[removal proceedings#Order of deportation|order of deportation]]" may be reviewed at any time by any [[Immigration Judge (United States)|immigration judge]] or any [[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] member and finally by any [[jurisdiction|authorized]] [[United States federal judge|federal judge]].<ref name="order of deportation">{{uscsub|8|1101|a|47}}; see generally ''[[Reyes Mata v. Lynch]]'', 576 U.S. ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/mata-v-lynch-1 135 S.Ct. 2150], 1253 (2015); ''Avalos-Suarez v. Whitaker'', [https://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/memoranda/2018/11/16/16-72773.pdf No. 16-72773] (9th Cir. Nov. 16, 2018) (unpublished); ''Nassiri v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/nassiri-v-sessions No. 16-60718] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|5th Cir.]] Dec. 14, 2017); ''Alimbaev v. Att'y'', [https://casetext.com/case/alimbaev-v-attorney-gen-of-the-united-states-1#p194 872 F.3d 188, 194] (3d Cir. 2017); ''Agonafer v. Sessions'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20170623158 859 F.3d 1198], 1202-03 (9th Cir. 2017); ''In re Baig'', [https://docmh.net/the-philosophy-of-money.html?utm_source=saadat-baig-a043-589-486-bia-jan-26-2017-plea-plea-bargain A043-589-486] (BIA Jan. 26, 2017) (unpublished three-member panel decision); ''In re Cisneros-Ramirez'', [https://www.scribd.com/document/322068486/J-Marcos-Cisneros-Ramirez-A090-442-154-BIA-Aug-9-2016 A 090-442-154] (BIA Aug. 9, 2016) (same); ''In re Contreras-Largaespada'', [https://www.scribd.com/document/303204885/Felix-Ramon-Contreras-Largaespada-A014-701-083-BIA-Feb-12-2016 A014-701-083] (BIA Feb. 12, 2016) (same); ''In re Wagner Aneudis Martinez'', [https://www.scribd.com/document/298582474/Wagner-Aneudis-Martinez-A043-447-800-BIA-Jan-12-2016 A043 447 800] (BIA Jan. 12, 2016) (same); ''In re Vikramjeet Sidhu'', [https://www.scribd.com/document/130627739/Vikramjeet-Sidhu-A044-238-062-BIA-Nov-30-2011 A044 238 062] (BIA Nov. 30, 2011) (same); accord ''Matter of A-N- & R-M-N-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3406.pdf 22 I&N Dec. 953] (BIA 1999) ([[en banc]]); ''Matter of G-N-C-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3366.pdf 22 I&N Dec. 281], 285 (BIA 1998) (en banc); ''Matter of JJ-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3323.pdf 21 I&N Dec. 976] ([[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] 1997) (en banc).</ref> Particular cases, especially those that were adjudicated in any [[United States district court|U.S. district court]] prior to the enactment of the [[Real ID Act of 2005]], can be reopened under [[Federal Rules of Civil Procedure#Title VII – Judgment|Rule 60]] of the [[Federal Rules of Civil Procedure]].<ref name="Rule 60">''United States v. Bueno-Sierra'', [https://www.courtlistener.com/pdf/2018/01/29/united_states_v._jorge_eliecer_bueno-sierra_1.pdf No. 17-12418], p.6-7 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|6th Cir.]] Jan. 29, 2018) ("Rule 60(b)(1) through (5) permits a district court to set aside an otherwise final judgment on a number of specific grounds, such as mistake, newly discovered evidence, an opposing party’s fraud, or a void or satisfied judgment. Rule 60(b)(6), the catch-all provision, authorizes a judgment to be set aside for 'any other reason that justifies relief.' Rule 60(d)(3) provides that Rule 60 does not limit a district court’s power to 'set aside a judgment for [[statute of limitations#Fraud upon the court|fraud on the court]].'") (citations omitted) (unpublished); ''Herring v. United States'', [https://casetext.com/case/herring-v-us-5#p387 424 F.3d 384], 386-87 (3d Cir. 2005) ("In order to meet the necessarily demanding standard for proof of [[statute of limitations#Fraud upon the court|fraud upon the court]] we conclude that there must be: (1) an intentional fraud; (2) by an officer of the court; (3) which is directed at the court itself; and (4) in fact deceives the court."); {{USC|18|371}}; {{USC|18|1001}} (court employees (including judges and clerks) have no immunity from prosecution under this section of law); ''Luna v. Bell'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20180405112 887 F.3d 290], 294 (6th Cir. 2018) ("Under Rule 60(b)(2), a party may request relief because of 'newly discovered evidence.'"); ''United States v. Handy'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [https://www.ca10.uscourts.gov/opinions/18/18-3086.pdf No. 18-3086], p.5-6 (10th Cir. July 18, 2018) ("Rule 60(b)(4) provides relief from void judgments, which are [[legal nullity|legal nullities]].... '''[W]hen Rule 60(b)(4) is applicable, relief is not a discretionary matter; it is mandatory. And the rule is not subject to any time limitation'''.") (citations, brackets, and internal quotation marks omitted); ''Mattis v. Vaughn'', [https://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/18D0392P.pdf No. 99-6533], p.3-4 ([[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania|E.D. Pa.]] June 4, 2018); accord ''Satterfield v. Dist. Att'y of Phila.'', [https://casetext.com/case/satterfield-v-dist-attorney-phila-2#p164 872 F.3d 152], 164 (3d Cir. 2017) ("The fact that . . . proceeding ended a decade ago should not preclude him from obtaining relief under Rule 60(b) if the court concludes that he has raised a [[color (law)|colorable]] claim that he meets this threshold [[actual innocence|actual-innocence]] standard ...."); see also ''[[United States v. Olano]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-olano#p736 507 U.S. 725], 736 (1993) ("In our collateral review jurisprudence, the term '[[miscarriage of justice]]' means that the defendant is actually innocent.... The court of appeals should no doubt correct a plain forfeited error that causes the conviction or sentencing of an actually innocent defendant....") (citations omitted); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 417|Davis v. United States]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/davis-v-united-states-8212-1454#p347 417 U.S. 333], 346-47 (1974) (regarding "[[miscarriage of justice]]" and "[[exceptional circumstances#United States|exceptional circumstances]]"); ''Gonzalez-Cantu v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/gonzalez-cantu-v-sessions#p306 866 F.3d 302], 306 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|5th Cir.]] 2017) (same) (collecting cases); ''Pacheco-Miranda v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/pacheco-miranda-v-sessions No. 14-70296] (9th Cir. Aug. 11, 2017) (same).</ref> The review of the order does not require the alien (or the [[Americans|American]]) to remain in the United States. It can be requested from anywhere in the world ''via'' [[express mail|mail]] (e.g., DHL, FedEx, UPS, Canada Post, etc.) and/or [[electronic court filing]] (ECF),<ref name="litigation from abroad">See generally ''Toor v. Lynch'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20150617177 789 F.3d 1055], 1064-65 (9th Cir. 2015) ("The regulatory departure bar [({{USCFR|8|1003.2}}(d))] is [[wikt:invalid#English|invalid]] irrespective of the manner in which the movant departed the United States, as it conflicts with clear and unambiguous statutory text.") (collecting cases); see also ''Blandino-Medina v. Holder'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20130410129 712 F.3d 1338], 1342 (9th Cir. 2013) ("An individual who has already been removed can satisfy the [[Case or Controversy Clause|case-or-controversy]] requirement by raising a direct challenge to the removal order."); ''United States v. Charleswell'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/2006803456f3d3471799 456 F.3d 347], 351 (3d Cir. 2006) (same); ''Kamagate v. Ashcroft'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/2004529385f3d1441512 385 F.3d 144], 150 (2d Cir. 2004) (same); ''Zegarra-Gomez v. INS'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20031438314f3d112411303 314 F.3d 1124], 1127 (9th Cir. 2003) (holding that because [[petitioner]]'s inability to return to the United States for twenty years as a result of his removal was "a concrete disadvantage imposed as a matter of law, the fact of his deportation did not render the pending [[habeas corpus in the United States|habeas petition]] moot").</ref> and the case can be filed in any court the alien (or the American) finds appropriate.<ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen.">''Ahmadi v. Ashcroft, et al.'', No. 03-249 ([[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania|E.D. Pa.]] Feb. 19, 2003) ("[[Petitioner]] in this [[habeas corpus in the United States|habeas corpus]] proceeding, entered the United States on September 30, 1982 as a [[refugee]] from his native [[Afghanistan]]. Two years later, the [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]] (the 'INS') [[Adjustment of status|adjusted Petitioner's status]] to that of a [[Permanent residence (United States)|lawful permanent resident]].... The INS timely appealed the [[Immigration Judge (United States)|Immigration Judge]]'s decision to the [[Board of Immigration Appeals]] (the 'BIA').") ([[Michael M. Baylson|Baylson]], District Judge); ''Ahmadi v. Att’y Gen.'', 659 F. App’x 72 (3d Cir. 2016) ([https://digitalcommons.law.villanova.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=2035&context=thirdcircuit_2016 Slip Opinion, pp.2, 4 n.1]) (invoking statutorily [[wikt:nullify|nullified]] [[wikt:case law|case law]], the court dismissed an obvious [[exceptional circumstances#United States|illegal deportation]] case by asserting that it lacks [[jurisdiction]] to review an unopposed [[Form N-400|United States nationality]] claim under {{uscsub|8|1252|b|5}} and {{uscsub|8|1252|f|2}} solely due to {{uscsub|8|1252|b|1}}) (non-precedential); ''Ahmadi v. Sessions'', No. 16-73974 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|9th Cir.]] Apr. 25, 2017) (same; unpublished single-paragraph order); ''Ahmadi v. Sessions'', No. 17-2672 (2d Cir. Feb. 22, 2018) (same; unpublished single-paragraph order); [[cf.]] ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 575|United States v. Wong]]'', 575 U.S. ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-wong-27#p1632 135 S.Ct. 1625], 1632 (2015) ("In recent years, we have repeatedly held that procedural rules, including time bars, cabin a [[jurisdiction|court's power]] only if Congress has clearly stated as much. Absent such a clear statement, ... courts should treat the restriction as '''non[[jurisdiction]]al'''.... And in applying that clear statement rule, we have made plain that most time bars are '''nonjurisdictional'''.") (citations, internal quotation marks, and brackets omitted) (emphasis added); see also ''Bibiano v. Lynch'', [https://casetext.com/case/bibiano-v-lynch#p971 834 F.3d 966], 971 (9th Cir. 2016) ("[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/8/1252#b_2 Section 1252(b)(2)] is a '''non-jurisdictional''' venue statute") (collecting cases) (emphasis added); ''Andreiu v. Ashcroft'', [https://casetext.com/case/andreiu-v-ashcroft#p482 253 F.3d 477], 482 (9th Cir. 2001) (en banc) (the court clarified "that § 1252(f)(2)'s standard for granting [[injunctive relief]] in [[removal proceedings]] [[wikt:trumps#English|trumps]] any contrary provision elsewhere in the law.").</ref>

Every illegal deportation claim, United States nationality claim, and CAT or asylum claim is adjudicated under 8 U.S.C. §§ 1252(a)(4), 1252(b)(4), 1252(b)(5), and 1252(f)(2). When these specific provisions are [[wikt:invoke#English|invoked]], all other contrary provisions of law, especially § 1252(b)(1) and any related case law, must be disregarded because these three claims manifestly constitute [[exceptional circumstances#United States|exceptional circumstances]].<ref name="Rule 60"/><ref name=American>''Khalid v. Sessions'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca2/16-3480/16-3480-2018-09-13.html No. 16‐3480], p.6 (2d Cir. Sept. 13, 2018) ("Khalid is a [[citizenship of the United States|U.S. citizen]] and the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) must [[cancellation of removal|terminate]] [[removal proceedings]] against him."); ''Jaen v. Sessions'', [http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/cf2ba23b-3ccb-41e7-a2f6-0d81ded289f6/4/doc/17-1512_opn.pdf 899 F.3d 182] (2d Cir. 2018) (same); ''Anderson v. Holder'', [https://casetext.com/case/anderson-v-holder-12#p1092 673 F.3d 1089], 1092 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|9th Cir.]] 2012) (same); ''Dent v. Sessions'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/dent-v-sessions-2 No. 17-15662], p.10-11 (9th Cir. Aug. 17, 2018) ("An individual has third-party standing when [(1)] the party asserting the right has a close relationship with the person who possesses the right [and (2)] there is a [[wikt:hindrance#English|hindrance]] to the possessor's ability to protect his own interests.") (quoting ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 582|Sessions v. Morales-Santana]]'', 582 U.S. ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/sessions-v-morales-santana#p1689 137 S.Ct. 1678], 1689 (2017)) (internal quotation marks omitted); ''Gonzalez-Alarcon v. Macias'', [https://casetext.com/case/gonzalez-alarcon-v-macias-1#p1270 884 F.3d 1266], 1270 (10th Cir. 2018); ''Hammond v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/hammond-v-sessions No. 16-3013], p.2-3 (2d Cir. Jan. 29, 2018) ("It is undisputed that Hammond's June 2016 motion to reconsider was untimely because his removal order became final in 2003.... Here, reconsideration was available only under the [[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]]'s [[sua sponte]] authority. {{uscfr|8|1003.2}}(a). Despite this procedural posture, we retain jurisdiction to review Hammond's U.S. [nationality] claim."); accord ''Duarte-Ceri v. Holder'', [https://casetext.com/case/duarte-ceri-v-holder#p87 630 F.3d 83, 87] (2d Cir. 2010) ("Duarte's legal claim encounters no jurisdictional obstacle because the [[United States Department of Justice|Executive Branch]] has no authority to remove a [national of the United States]."); {{uscfr|8|239.2}}; see also ''Yith v. Nielsen'', [https://casetext.com/case/yith-v-nielsen-1#p1159 881 F.3d 1155], 1159 (9th Cir. 2018) ("Once applicants have exhausted administrative remedies, they may appeal to a district court."); {{uscsub|8|1447|b}} ("Request for hearing before district court").</ref><ref name="U.S. nationality claim"/><ref name="injunctive relief"/><ref name="injunctive relief 2"/> In [[removal proceedings]], the focus is simply on whether or not the person belongs in the United States as a matter of law. If he or she does then dismissing the case for lack of [[jurisdiction]] or [[wikt:hinder#English|delaying]] relief is plainly [[wikt:counterproductive#English|counterproductive]].<ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name=CAT/><ref name="CQ Press"/><ref name=LexisNexis/><ref name=Document171/><ref name=anti-discrimination/><ref name="Kennedy v. Mendoza-Martinez"/> The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] has pointed out in 2009 that "the context surrounding IIRIRA's enactment suggests that § 1252(f)(2) was an important—not a superfluous—statutory provision."<ref name="Nken v. Holder">''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 556|Nken v. Holder]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/nken-v-holder-4#p443 556 U.S. 418], 443 (2009) ([[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Samuel Alito|Alito]] dissenting with Justice [[Clarence Thomas|Thomas]]).</ref> In this regard, Congress has long warned U.S. public officials by expressly stating the following:{{Quote|[[Wikt:Whoever#English|Whoever]], under [[color (law)|color of any law]], [[statutory law|statute]], [[local ordinance|ordinance]], [[Federal Register|regulation]], or [[custom (law)|custom]], [[wikt:wilfully#English|willfully]] subjects '''''any [[person]]''''' in any [[U.S. state|State]], [[Territories of the United States|Territory]], or [[Washington, D.C.|District]] to the [[wikt:deprivation#English|deprivation]] of any [[human rights in the United States|rights]], [[wikt:privilege#English|privileges]], or [[wikt:immunity#English|immunities]] secured or protected by the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] or [[law of the United States|laws]] of the United States, or to different [[punishment]]s, [[wikt:pain#English|pains]], or [[wikt:penalty#English|penalties]], <u>on account of such person being an '''''[[alien (law)#United States|alien]]'''''</u>, or by reason of his [[color terminology for race|color]], or [[race and ethnicity in the United States|race]], than are prescribed for the punishment of [[citizenship of the United States|citizens]], ''shall'' be subject to specified criminal penalties.<ref>''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 520|United States v. Lanier]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-lanier-2#p265 520 U.S. 259], 264-65 n.3 (1997) (internal quotation marks omitted) (emphasis added).</ref><ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name="war crimes"/><ref name=CAT/><ref name="CQ Press"/><ref name=anti-discrimination/>}}

According to § 1252(f)(1), "no court (other than the Supreme Court)" is [[jurisdiction|authorized]] to determine which two or more people in removal proceedings should be recognized as [[nationals of the United States]] ([[Americans]]).<ref name="injunctive relief">''[[Jennings v. Rodriguez]]'', 583 U.S. ___, 138 S.Ct. 830, 875 (2018) ([https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/15-1204_f29g.pdf p.42 here]); ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.|Wheaton College v. Burwell]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/wheaton-coll-v-burwell#p2811 134 S.Ct. 2806], 2810-11 (2014) ("Under our [[precedent]]s, an [[injunction]] is appropriate only if (1) it is necessary or appropriate in aid of our [[jurisdiction]], and (2) the legal rights at issue are indisputably clear.") (internal quotation marks and brackets omitted); ''[[2009 term United States Supreme Court opinions of John Roberts|Lux v. Rodrigues]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/lux-v-rodrigues 561 U.S. 1306], 1308 (2010); ''[[Correctional Services Corp. v. Malesko]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/correctional-services-corporation-v-malesko#p74 534 U.S. 61], 74 (2001) (stating that "[[injunction|injunctive relief]] has long been recognized as the proper means for preventing entities from acting unconstitutionally."); ''Alli v. Decker'', [https://casetext.com/case/alli-v-decker-2#p1011 650 F.3d 1007], 1010-11 (3d Cir. 2011) (same); ''Andreiu v. Ashcroft'', [https://casetext.com/case/andreiu-v-ashcroft#p482 253 F.3d 477], 482-85 (9th Cir. 2001) (en banc) (same); see also {{uscsub|8|1326|d}} ("Limitation on collateral attack on underlying [[removal proceedings#Order of deportation|deportation order]]").</ref> This includes parents and children or relatives.<ref name="nationals but not citizens of the United States"/><ref name=American/> The remaining courts, however, are fully [[jurisdiction|empowered]] by §§ 1252(b)(5) and 1252(f)(2) to, ''[[inter alia]]'', issue an [[injunction]] to [[cancellation of removal|cancel or terminate]] any person's removal proceedings; return any removed person to the United States; and/or to confer United States nationality upon any person (but only using a case-by-case analysis).<ref name="injunctive relief"/><ref name="injunctive relief 2">''Singh v. USCIS'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20171222065 878 F.3d 441], 443 (2d Cir. 2017) ("The government conceded that Singh's removal was improper.... Consequently, in May 2007, Singh was temporarily paroled back into the United States by the Attorney General, who exercised his discretion to grant temporary parole to certain aliens."); ''Orabi v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/orabi-v-attorney-gen-of-the-united-states#p543 738 F.3d 535], 543 (3d Cir. 2014) ("The judgment of the [[Board of Immigration Appeals|BIA]] will therefore be reversed, with instructions that the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Government]]... be directed to return Orabi to the United States in accordance with the [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] regulations cited."); ''Avalos-Palma v. United States'', [https://casetext.com/case/avalos-palma-v-united-states#p3 No. 13-5481 (FLW)], 2014 WL 3524758, p.3 ([[United States District Court for the District of New Jersey|D.N.J.]] July 16, 2014) ("On June 2, 2012, approximately 42 months after the improper deportation, [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] agents effectuated Avalos-Palma's return to the United States."); ''In re Vikramjeet Sidhu'', [https://www.scribd.com/document/130627739/Vikramjeet-Sidhu-A044-238-062-BIA-Nov-30-2011 A044 238 062], at 1-2 (BIA Nov. 30, 2011) ("As related in his brief on appeal, the respondent was physically removed from the United States in June 2004, but subsequently returned to this country under a grant of [[advance parole|humanitarian parole]].... Accordingly, the proceedings will be terminated.") (three-member panel).</ref><ref name=American/> In addition to that, under {{uscfr|8|239.2}}, any officer mentioned in {{uscfr|8|239.1}} may at any time move to: (1) terminate the case of any person who turns out to be an American; or (2) cancel the removal of anyone who is clearly not removable under the INA.<ref name="Matter of S-O-G- & F-D-B-">''Matter of S-O-G- & F-D-B-'', [https://www.justice.gov/eoir/page/file/1095371/download 27 I&N Dec. 462] (A.G. 2018) ("[[Immigration Judge (United States)|Immigration judges]] may dismiss or terminate [[removal proceedings]] only under the circumstances expressly identified in the regulations, ''see'' {{USCFR|8|1239.2}}(c), (f), or where the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] fails to sustain the charges of removability against a respondent, ''see'' {{USCFR|8|1240.12}}(c)."); see also ''Matter of G-N-C-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3366.pdf 22 I&N Dec. 281] (BIA 1998) (en banc).</ref> The [[burden of proof (law)|burden]] is on the alien (or the American) to establish eligibility for relief.

==Legal conflict between an aggravated felony and a misdemeanor==
According to the Third Circuit, New York's [[misdemeanor]] "petit [[larceny]]" qualifies as an aggravated felony under {{uscsub|8|1101|a|43|G}} but only if the trial court or sentencing court orders at least one year of [[imprisonment]]. Any "street time" (i.e., period of [[probation]], [[parole]], or [[United States federal probation and supervised release|supervised release]]) that was ordered by the court as part of the defendant's sentence or punishment does not count as term of imprisonment.<ref name="street time">{{uscsub|8|1101|a|48|B}}; ''In re Juan Ignacio Ruela'', [http://www.irac.net/unpublished/juan-ignacio-ruela-a077-485-879-bia-may-5-2014/ A077 485 879] (BIA May 5, 2014); accord ''Matter of Cota'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3522.pdf 23 I&N Dec. 849], 852 (BIA 2005); ''United States v. Pray'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-pray-2#p361 373 F.3d 358], 361 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit|3d Cir.]] 2004) ("We hold that the term '[[imprisonment]]' ... does not include parole.... A person who is on parole, although subject to some restraints on liberty, is not 'imprisoned' in the sense in which the term is usually used. For example, if a parolee were informed at the end of a parole revocation hearing that the outcome was 'imprisonment,' the parolee would not think that this meant that he was going to be returned to parole.") (citations omitted); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 282|United States v. Benz]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-benz-2#p307 282 U.S. 304], 306-07 (1931); ''United States v. Pettus'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-pettus-2 303 F.3d 480] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|2d Cir.]] 2002) (regarding "street time"); ''Young v. Pa. Board of Probation and Parole'', [https://caselaw.findlaw.com/pa-commonwealth-court/1897776.html No. 361 C.D. 2016] ([[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania|Commonwealth Court of Pa.]] June 12, 2018) ("However, if the Parole Board does award credit, the parolee no longer has ''''time spent at liberty on parole,' i.e., 'street time.'''' Id.") (emphasis added); ''Commonwealth v. Conahan'', [https://casetext.com/case/com-v-conahan#p202 589 A.2d 1107], 1110 ([[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania|Pa.]] 1991); ''Young v. Pa. Board of Probation and Parole'', [https://casetext.com/case/young-v-com-bd-of-probation-and-parole#p434 409 A.2d 843], 846-47 (Pa. 1979) ("To attempt to equate a parole status with that of custody is to ignore reality."); accord ''[[Morrissey v. Brewer]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/morrissey-v-brewer-2#p482 408 U.S. 471], 482 (1972).</ref><ref name="Garcia-Mendoza v. Holder">''Garcia-Mendoza v. Holder'', [https://casetext.com/case/garcia-mendoza-v-holder#p1169 753 F.3d 1165], 1169 (10th Cir. 2014).</ref> A sentence of imprisonment with parole is called a "bifurcated sentence,"<ref>''State v. Cole'', [https://casetext.com/case/state-v-cole-325#p178 262 Wis.2d 167], 177, 663 N.W.2d 700 ([[Wisconsin Supreme Court|Wis.]] 2003).</ref> and various [[United States courts of appeals|U.S. courts of appeals]] have held that this is not a [[suspended sentence]].<ref name="street time 2">''United States v. Parsons'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-parsons-18#p10 No. 15-2055], at p.10 (3d Cir. Nov. 10, 2016); accord ''United States v. Frias'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-frias-2#p211 338 F.3d 206], 211 (3d Cir. 2003); ''United States v. Rodriguez-Bernal'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-rodriguez-bernal-2#p1006 783 F.3d 1002], 1006 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|5th Cir.]] 2015); ''United States v. Rodriguez-Arreola'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-rodriguez-arreola-3#p1066 313 F.3d 1064], 1066 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|8th Cir.]] 2002); see also {{uscsub|18|924|e|1}} ("In the case of a person who violates [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/922#g section 922(g)] ... the court shall not '''''suspend the sentence''''' of, '''''or''''' grant a '''''probationary sentence''''' to, such person ....") (emphasis added); 42 Pa. Cons. Stat. [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/LI/CT/HTM/42/00.097.056.000..HTM § 9756(b)] ("The court ''shall'' impose a minimum sentence of confinement which ''shall'' not exceed one-half of the maximum sentence imposed.") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="Alabama v. Bozeman"/> Regarding the legal conflict between an aggravated felony and a misdemeanor, Judge [[Edward Roy Becker|Edward Becker]] of the Third Circuit stated the following:{{Quote|The line between [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|felonies and misdemeanors]] is an ancient one. The line has not always been drawn between one year and one year and a day, since it used to be that felonies were all punishable by death.... Furthermore, under federal law, a felony is defined as a crime that has a maximum term of more than one year.... Because, as the government contends, the amended statute's definition of an aggravated theft felony refers to sentences actually imposed and not to potential sentences, it is still possible for a [defendant] to avoid being an aggravated felon if he or she receives a six-month sentence for a theft crime with a maximum possible sentence over one year....<ref>''United States v. Graham'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-graham-44#p792 169 F.3d 787], 792 (3d Cir. 1999); see also ''Francis v. Reno'', [https://casetext.com/case/francis-v-reno#p167 269 F.3d 162], 167-71 (3d Cir. 2001)</ref>}}

It is important to note that a court cannot [[violation of law|defy]] a clearly-established law.<ref name="statutory interpretation"/> Under the INA, a crime must be punishable by imprisonment for a term "exceeding" one year in order to be considered a "crime involving moral turpitude" or an aggravated felony.<ref name=CIMT/><ref name=removable/><ref name=a-f-1988/><ref>''[[Alabama v. Shelton]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/alabama-v-shelton-3#p670 535 U.S. 654], 670 n.10 (2002) ("In Pennsylvania, for example, ... only those charged with '[[summary offence|summary offenses]]' (violations not technically considered crimes and punishable by no more than 90 days' imprisonment, ... may receive a suspended sentence uncounseled. (Typical 'summary offenses' in Pennsylvania include the failure to return a library book within 30 days, ... and fishing on a Sunday [.])" (citations omitted).</ref> Anything to the contrary will lead to an absurd result and a blatant violation of the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]].<ref name=DOJ/><ref name="civil rights"/><ref name=CAT>{{cite web |url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CAT.aspx |title=Article 16|publisher=[[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] |accessdate=July 15, 2018|quote=[The United States] shall undertake to prevent in any territory under its jurisdiction other acts of '''cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment''' which do not amount to [[torture]] as defined in article I, when such acts are committed by or at the instigation of or with the consent or acquiescence of a public official or other person acting in an official capacity.}} (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="CQ Press">{{cite web |title=Chapter 11 - Foreign Policy: Senate OKs Ratification of Torture Treaty |url=http://library.cqpress.com/cqalmanac/document.php?id=cqal90-1118781&type=toc&num=15 |publisher=[[CQ Press]]|edition=46th |pages=806–7|year=1990|accessdate=August 8, 2018|quote=The three other reservations, also crafted with the help and approval of the [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|Bush administration]], did the following: Limited the definition of <u>'cruel, inhuman or degrading' treatment</u> to [[cruel and unusual punishment]] as defined under the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth]], [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Eighth]] and [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|14th]] Amendments to the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]]....}} (emphasis added).</ref> Plus, it will damage the reputation of the [[appellate court]],<ref>''[[United States v. Olano]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-olano#p732 507 U.S. 725], 732 (1993).</ref> which suppose to play a more neutral role in [[removal proceedings]] under the INA because they are obviously not criminal proceedings.<ref name="burden of proof"/><ref name="order of deportation"/> Congress has long stated in {{uscsub|18|921|a|20}} that "[t]he term [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|[aggravated felony]]] does not include . . . any [[U.S. state|State]] [[crime|offense]] classified by the laws of the State as a [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|misdemeanor]] and punishable by a term of imprisonment of two years or less." This expressed language of Congress was in effect in 1988 (when the aggravated felony was coined for the first time) and is still in effect today.<ref name=a-f-1988/>

Section 921(a)(20) applies to the entire [[title 18 of the United States Code#Chapters 11–123|Chapter 44 (§§ 921-931)]] of title 18. As such, § 921(a)(20) controls 8 U.S.C. § 1101(a)(43), especially subparagraphs (A), (B), (C), (D), (E), (F), and (G).<ref name="United States v. Barret"/> Under § 921(a)(20), Congress says this: "What constitutes a conviction of such a crime shall be determined in accordance with the law of the jurisdiction in which the proceedings were held." This simply means that the [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|federal felony]] definition controls in all immigration-related cases.<ref>''[[Lopez v. Gonzales]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/lopez-v-gonzales-no-05-547-us-1252006 549 U.S. 47] (2006) ("The question raised is whether conduct made a felony under state law but a misdemeanor under the Controlled Substances Act is a "felony punishable under the Controlled Substances Act." {{uscsub|18|924|c|2}}. '''We hold it is not'''.") (emphasis added).</ref> More importantly, in [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/927 § 927] ("Effect on State law"), Congress expressly states: "No provision of [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/part-I/chapter-44 this chapter] shall be construed as indicating an intent on the part of the Congress to occupy the field in which such provision operates to the exclusion of the law of any State on the same subject matter. . . ." The phrase "[n]o provision of this chapter" statutorily covers (among many other crimes) every [[violent crime|crime of violence]] and [[theft]].<ref name="United States v. Barret">See generally ''United States v. Barret'', ___ F.3d ___, [http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/353f14ed-7d59-454a-9a91-e88265d5782d/1/doc/14-2641_opn.pdf No. 14-2641-cr] (2d Cir. Sept. 10, 2018); ''United States v. Pereira-Gomez'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/d390847a-400e-4849-9753-d905dd801031/3/doc/17-952_opn.pdf No. 17-952-cr], p.6 note 4 (2d Cir. Sept. 7, 2018) (defining "crime of violence").</ref> See also the below section: ''[[Aggravated felony#Comparison of an aggravated felony to a crime involving moral turpitude|Comparison of an aggravated felony to a crime involving moral turpitude]]''.

===Precedents relating to "crime of violence" under U.S. law===
In 2001, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|Fifth Circuit]] held "that because intentional force against the person or property of another is seldom, if ever, employed to commit the offense of felony [[Driving under the influence|DWI]], such offense is not a [[violent crime|crime of violence]] within the meaning of {{uscsub|18|16|b}}."<ref>''United States v. Chapa-Garza'', [https://casetext.com/case/chapa-garza#p928 243 F.3d 921], 928 (5th Cir. 2001).</ref> Later in the same year, the Third Circuit held that unintentional [[vehicular homicide]] is not an aggravated felony under {{uscsub|8|1101|a|43|F}}.<ref>''Francis v. Reno'', [https://casetext.com/case/francis-v-reno#p171 269 F.3d 162], 171-75 (3d Cir. 2001).</ref> In ''[[Leocal v. Ashcroft]]'', {{ussc|543|1|2004}}, the U.S. Supreme Court held that [[Drunk driving in the United States|driving under the influence]] is not an aggravated felony if the DUI statute that defines the offense does not contain a ''[[mens rea]]'' element or otherwise allows a conviction for merely negligent conduct.

In ''Popal v. Gonzales'', [https://casetext.com/case/popal-v-gonzales 416 F.3d 249] (3d Cir. 2005), the Third Circuit held that a Pennsylvania "simple [[assault]]," which is a misdemeanor of the second degree (punishable by two years or less), does not constitute a crime of violence under § 16(a) and is therefore not an aggravate felony.<ref>A number of the remaining circuits have agreed and adopted this conclusion, see, e.g., ''Fernandez-Ruiz v. Gonzales'' [https://casetext.com/case/fernandez-ruiz-v-gonzales-3#p1129 466 F.3d 1121], 1129 (9th Cir. 2006) (en banc).</ref> "And the Supreme Court recently declared, in ''[[Sessions v. Dimaya]]'', 138 S. Ct. 1204, 1223 (2018), that § 16(b) is unconstitutionally vague and, therefore, cannot be the basis for an aggravated felony."<ref>''Dent v. Sessions'', ___ F.3d ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/dent-v-sessions-2#p21 No. 17-15662], p.21 (9th Cir. Aug. 17, 2018); see also ''Mateo v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20170906069 870 F.3d 228] (3d Cir. 2017) (same).</ref>

==Comparison of an aggravated felony to a crime involving moral turpitude==
The term "crime involving [[moral turpitude]]" (CIMT) in the INA refers to a specific criminal conviction in which a court of law has imposed upon an alien a "term of [[imprisonment]] in excess of 6 months (regardless of the extent to which the sentence was ultimately executed)."<ref name=CIMT>{{uscsub|8|1182|a|2|A|ii|II}}; {{uscsub|8|1101|f|7}}; see also, generally ''Arias v. Lynch'', [https://casetext.com/case/arias-v-lynch#p831 834 F.3d 823], 831 (7th Cir. 2016); ''Flores-Molina v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/flores-molina-v-sessions#p1172 850 F.3d 1150], 1171-72 (10th Cir. 2017) (collecting cases); ''Ildefonso-Candelario v. Att’y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/ildefonso-candelario-v-attorney-gen-of-the-united-states#p106 866 F.3d 102], 105-06 n.4 (3d Cir. 2017); ''Lozano-Arredondo v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/lozano-arredondo-v-sessions#p1086 866 F.3d 1082], 1086 (9th Cir. 2017); ''Romero v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/romero-v-sessions-2 Nos. 16-73655, 17-70848] (9th Cir. June 1, 2018) (unpublished); ''Garcia-Martinez v. Sessions'', [https://casetext.com/case/garcia-martinez-v-sessions#p8 886 F.3d 1291], 1294 (9th Cir. 2018); ''Beltran-Tirado v. INS'', [https://casetext.com/case/beltran-tirado-v-ins#p1183 213 F.3d 1179], 1183 (9th Cir. 2000); ''Matter of Serna'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2012/08/14/3188.pdf 20 I&N Dec. 579], 584 (BIA 1992); ''Matter of Espinosa'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2012/08/27/1250.pdf 10 I&N Dec. 98] (BIA 1962); ''Matter of G-'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2012/08/27/Pg315.pdf 8 I&N Dec. 315] (BIA 1959).</ref><ref name=removable/> Congress made a clear distinction between "[[lawful permanent residents (United States)|permanent residents]]" and "nonpermanent residents" in this regard.<ref name=CIMT2>{{uscsub|8|1229b|a}} ("[[Cancellation of removal]] for certain permanent residents"); {{uscsub|8|1229b|b}} ("Cancellation of removal and [[adjustment of status]] for certain nonpermanent residents") see also {{uscsub|8|1227|a}} ("Any alien (including an alien crewman) in and admitted to the United States shall, ... be removed if the alien is within one or more of the following classes of [remov]able aliens:.... Any alien who at the time of ... [[adjustment of status]] was within one or more of the classes of aliens [[wikt:inadmissible#English|inadmissible]] by the law existing at such time [or] who is present in the United States in violation of th[e] [INA] or any other law of the United States, ... is [remov]able."); but see ''Matter of Ortega-Lopez'', [https://www.justice.gov/eoir/page/file/1085471/download 27 I&N Dec. 382], 391-98 (BIA 2018) (coming to a conflicting conclusion); ''Matter of Velasquez-Rios'', [https://www.justice.gov/eoir/page/file/1098611/download 27 I&N Dec. 470] (BIA 2018) (same).</ref><ref name="burden of proof">''Edwards v. Sessions'', [http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/6ddd4da4-2050-4f74-b14b-f619b36aa9a2/2/doc/17-87_so.pdf No. 17-87], p.3 (2d Cir. Aug. 24, 2018) ("In [[removal proceedings]] involving an [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|LPR]], the [[United States Attorney General|government]] bears the burden of proof, which it must meet by adducing [[burden of proof (law)#Beyond reasonable doubt|clear, unequivocal, and convincing evidence]] that the facts alleged as grounds for deportation are true.") (internal quotation marks omitted) (summary order); accord {{uscfr|8|1240.46}}(a); {{uscsub|8|1229a|b|5|A}}; ''Mondaca-Vega v. Lynch'', [https://casetext.com/case/mondaca-vega-v-lynch#p429 808 F.3d 413], 429 (9th Cir. 2015) ("The burden of proof required for [[burden of proof (law)#Beyond reasonable doubt|clear, unequivocal, and convincing evidence]] is greater than the burden of proof required for [[burden of proof (law)#Clear and convincing evidence|clear and convincing evidence]]."); ''Ward v. Holder'', [https://casetext.com/case/ward-v-holder-3#p605 733 F.3d 601], 604–05 (6th Cir. 2013); ''United States v. Thompson-Riviere'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20090326081 561 F.3d 345], 349 (4th Cir. 2009) ("To convict him of this offense, the government bore the burden of proving [[burden of proof (law)#Beyond reasonable doubt|beyond a reasonable doubt]] that (inter alia) he is an 'alien,' which means he is 'not a citizen or [[national of the United States]],'" (citations omitted); ''Francis v. Gonzales'', [https://casetext.com/case/francis-v-gonzales#p138 442 F.3d 131], 138 (2d Cir. 2006); ''Matter of Pichardo'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3275.pdf 21 I&N Dec. 330], 333 (BIA 1996) ([[en banc]]); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 385|Berenyi v. Immigration Dir.]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/berenyi-v-immigration-director#p637 385 U.S. 630], 636-37 (1967) ("When the Government seeks to strip a person of [United States nationality] already [[wikt:acquire#English|acquired]], or deport a [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|resident alien]] and send him from our shores, it carries the heavy burden of proving its case by 'clear, unequivocal, and convincing evidence.' . . . [T]hat status, once granted, cannot lightly be taken away...." (footnotes omitted)); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 385|Woodby v. INS]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/woodby-v-immigration-service#p285 385 U.S. 276], 285 (1966); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 364|Chaunt v. United States]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/chaunt-v-united-states#p353 364 U.S. 350], 353 (1960).</ref> In the case of a permanent resident, the CIMT must be committed within 5 years of his or her admission to the United States.<ref name=CIMT2/> However, despite the obvious differences, both classes of aliens are statutorily entitled to [[waiver of inadmissibility (United States)|waiver of inadmissibility]] and [[cancellation of removal]], so long as "the '''''maximum penalty possible''''' for the crime of which the alien[s] w[ere] convicted . . . '''''did not exceed imprisonment for one year''''' . . . ." (emphasis added).<ref name=CIMT/><ref name=removable/> Any period of incarceration or confinement that was subsequently added due to probation/parole violation plainly does not count.<ref name="street time"/><ref name="street time 2"/> If the total period served inside a [[prison|penal institution]] (for all past convictions) was less than 180 days (6 months),<ref name="Garcia-Mendoza v. Holder"/> the permanent resident is manifestly entitled to [[national of the United States|U.S. nationality]] and [[citizenship of the United States|citizenship]], provided that the remaining nationality and citizenship requirements are fulfilled.<ref name=American/> Such person may be naturalized in the United States or (in particular cases) at any [[list of diplomatic missions of the United States|U.S. embassy]] around the world.<ref>{{uscsub|8|1445|e}} ("A person may file an [[Form N-400|application for naturalization]] other than in the office of the Attorney General, and an oath of allegiance administered other than in a public ceremony before the Attorney General or a court, if the Attorney General determines that the person has an illness or other disability which—(1) is of a permanent nature and is sufficiently serious to prevent the person's personal appearance, '''''or (2) is of a nature which so [[wikt:incapacitate#English|incapacitates]] the person as to prevent him from personally appearing'''''.") (emphasis added); see also {{uscsub|8|1446|a}} ("The Attorney General may, in his [[discretion]], '''''waive''''' a personal investigation in an individual case or in such cases or classes of cases as may be designated by him.") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name=American/><ref name="U.S. nationality claim"/><ref name="injunctive relief"/><ref name="Nken v. Holder"/><ref name="Ahmadi v. Att'y Gen."/>

The consequences of making a crime an "aggravated felony" are far reaching. One major consequence is that, unlike the [[deportation]] ground for a CIMT, an aggravated felony does not necessarily have to be committed within five years from the alien's entry or admission to the United States to make him or her removable.<ref name=removable/> In other words, an alien who cannot demonstrate U.S. nationality is removable even if he or she has committed an aggravated felony in a foreign country before entering the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspected Islamic State member accused of killing police officer in Iraq arrested in Sacramento, where he settled as a refugee |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-iraq-murder-20180815-story.html |date=August 15, 2018 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |work=Alene Tchekmedyian |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> In this regard, the INA expressly states the following:{{Quote|<u>The term [aggravated felony] applies to an offense described in this paragraph</u> whether in violation of Federal or State law '''''and''''' applies to such an offense in violation of the law of a foreign country <u>for which the term of imprisonment was completed within the previous 15 years</u>. '''''Notwithstanding any other provision of law''''' (including any effective date), the term [aggravated felony] applies regardless of whether the conviction was entered before, on, or after September 30, 1996.<ref name=a-f-1996/>}}

"The ordinary meaning of 'notwithstanding' is 'in spite of,' or 'without prevention or obstruction from or by.'"<ref name="NLRB v. SW General, Inc.">''[[NLRB v. SW General, Inc.]]'', 580 U.S. ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/natl-labor-relations-bd-v-sw-gen-inc#p939 137 S.Ct. 929], 939 (2017).</ref> Congress is clearly and unambiguously saying that the penultimate provision under 8 U.S.C. § 1101(a)(43), as quoted above,
controls over § 1101(f)(8), 1227(a)(2)(A)(iii), 1427(a), etc. "In statutes, the [notwithstanding any other provision of law] 'shows which provision prevails in the event of a clash.'"<ref name="NLRB v. SW General, Inc."/> Courts have explained that "the phrase 'notwithstanding any other provision of law' expresses the legislative intent to override all contrary statutory '''and''' [[decisional law]]."<ref name="notwithstanding clause">''In re JMC Telecom LLC'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20091154416aibr73811120 416 B.R. 738], 743 ([[United States District Court for the Central District of California|C.D. Cal.]] 2009) (internal quotation marks and brackets omitted) (emphasis added) ([[Howard Matz|A. Howard Matz]], District Judge); see also ''In re Partida'', [https://casetext.com/case/partida-v-us-dept-of-justice-in-re-partida-1#p912 862 F.3d 909], 912 (9th Cir. 2017) ("That is the function and purpose of the 'notwithstanding' clause."); ''Drakes Bay Oyster Co. v. Jewell'', [https://casetext.com/case/drakes-bay-oyster-co-v-jewell#p1083 747 F.3d 1073], 1083 (9th Cir. 2014) ("As a general matter, 'notwithstanding' clauses nullify conflicting provisions of law."); ''Jones v. United States'', [https://casetext.com/case/jones-v-us-394#p5 No. 08-645C], p.4-5 ([[United States Court of Federal Claims|Fed. Cl.]] Sep. 14, 2009); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 558|Kucana v. Holder]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/kucana-v-holder-7#N196680 558 U.S. 233], 238-39 n.1 (2010); ''Andreiu v. Ashcroft'', [https://casetext.com/case/andreiu-v-ashcroft#p482 253 F.3d 477], 482 (9th Cir. 2001) (en banc) (the court clarified "that § 1252(f)(2)'s standard for granting injunctive relief in removal proceedings [[wikt:trumps#English|trumps]] any contrary provision elsewhere in the law."); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 508|Cisneros v. Alpine Ridge Group]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/cisneros-v-alpine-ridge-group#p18 508 U.S. 10], 18 (1993) (collecting cases).</ref> What this means is that holdings such as ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 514|Stone v. INS]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/stone-v-ins-2#p405 514 U.S. 386], 405 (1995) (case obviously decided prior to IIRIRA of 1996, which materially changed the old "judicial review provisions of the INA"),<ref name="Othi v. Holder">''Othi v. Holder'', [https://casetext.com/case/othi-v-holder#p265 734 F.3d 259], 264-65 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|4th Cir.]] 2013) ("In 1996, Congress 'made major changes to immigration law' via IIRIRA. . . . These IIRIRA changes became effective on April 1, 1997.").</ref> are statutorily not binding upon any agency or any court.<ref>''[[Citizens United v. FEC]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/citizens-united-v-federal-election-comn#p362 558 U.S. 310], 362-63 (2010) ("Our [[precedent]] is to be respected unless the most convincing of reasons demonstrates that adherence to it puts us on a course that is sure error."); see also ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 495|Missouri v. Jenkins]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/missouri-v-jenkins#p45 495 U.S. 33], 45 (1990) ("We have no authority to extend the period for filing except as Congress permits."); cf. ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 575|United States v. Wong]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-wong-27#p1632 135 S.Ct. 1625], 1632 (2015).</ref><ref>''Garcia v. Att'y Gen.'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20090114099 553 F.3d 724], 727 (3d Cir. 2009) ("We are bound by [[precedent]]ial opinions of our Court unless they have been . . . adversely affected by an opinion of the [[United States Supreme Court|Supreme Court]].); see also ''Miller v. Gammie'', [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20031224335f3d88911115 335 F.3d 889], 900 (9th Cir. 2003) (en banc) ("We hold that the issues decided by the higher court need not be identical in order to be controlling. Rather, the relevant court of last resort must have undercut the theory or reasoning underlying the prior circuit precedent in such a way that the cases are clearly irreconcilable.").</ref><ref name="Rule 60"/> Congress clearly spoken about this at {{uscsub|8|1252|d|2}} (eff. 1996). Its intent was sufficiently shown when amending § 1252 during the enactment of the [[Real ID Act]] of 2005. There, it added "(statutory or nonstatutory)" after every relevant "notwithstanding any other provision of law" in § 1252.<ref>{{cite web |title=H.R. Rep. No. 109-72: SEC. 106. JUDICIAL REVIEW OF ORDERS OF REMOVAL. |url=https://www.congress.gov/109/crpt/hrpt72/CRPT-109hrpt72.pdf |pages=80–82 |date= May 3, 2005 |accessdate=2018-07-16|publisher=United States Congress}}</ref> The overall purpose of this is obviously to protect the United States<ref>{{cite web|title=ICE attorney sentenced to nearly 18 years on corruption charges stemming from multi-agency probe involving ICE OPR |url=https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ice-attorney-sentenced-nearly-18-years-corruption-charges-stemming-multi-agency-probe |date=March 21, 2011 |publisher=U.S. Dept. of Homeland Security |accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Homeland Security agents took $15M in bribes, closed their eyes |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/homeland-security-agents-took-15m-in-bribes-closed-their-eyes/ |date=December 28, 2016 |work=Ron Nixon, The New York Times |publisher=The Seattle Times |accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Immigration Officer Bribe Arrest Adds to Homeland Security Corruption Woes |url=https://www.newsweek.com/immigration-officer-fraud-bribe-arrest-miami-612648 |date=May 19, 2017 |first=Josh |last=Saul |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref> and the over 13 million<ref name=Lee>{{cite news|title=Estimates of the Lawful Permanent Resident Population in the United States: January 2014 |url=https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/LPR%20Population%20Estimates%20January%202014.pdf |publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security|U.S. Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) |work=James Lee; Bryan Baker |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> [[lawful permanent residents (United States)|lawful permanent residents]] against lawless government actions.<ref name=DOJ>{{cite web|title=Deprivation Of Rights Under Color Of Law |url=https://www.justice.gov/crt/deprivation-rights-under-color-law |date=August 6, 2015 |publisher=U.S. Department of Justice (DOJ) |accessdate=2018-08-17 |quote=[https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/242 Section 242 of Title 18] makes it a [[crime]] for a person acting under color of any law to willfully deprive a person of a right or privilege protected by the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] or [[law of the United States|laws of the United States]]. For the purpose of Section 242, acts under '[[color (law)|color of law]]' include acts not only done by federal, state, or local officials within the their lawful authority, but also acts done beyond the bounds of that official's lawful authority, if the acts are done while the official is purporting to or pretending to act in the performance of his/her official duties. '''Persons acting under color of law within the meaning of this statute include police officers, prisons guards and other [[list of law enforcement agencies#United States|law enforcement officials]], as well as [[United States federal judge|judges]], care providers in public health facilities, and others who are acting as public officials'''. It is not necessary that the crime be motivated by animus toward the race, color, religion, sex, handicap, familial status or national origin of the victim. The offense is punishable by a range of imprisonment up to a life term, or the death penalty, depending upon the circumstances of the crime, and the resulting injury, if any.}} (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="civil rights">{{usc|18|241|249}}; ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 520|United States v. Lanier]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-lanier-2#p264 520 U.S. 259], 264 (1997) ("Section [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/242 242] is a [[Reconstruction Era]] civil rights statute making it criminal to act (1) '[[willfully]]' and (2) under [[color (law)|color of law]] (3) to deprive a person of rights protected by the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] or [[Law of the United States|laws of the United States]]."); ''United States v. Lanier'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-lanier-11 123 F.3d 945] (6th Cir. 1997); ''[[Hope v. Pelzer]]'', [https://casetext.com/case/hope-v-pelzer-9#p737 536 U.S. 730], 736-37 (2002); ''United States v. Acosta'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-acosta-77#p136 470 F.3d 132], 136 (2d Cir. 2006) (holding that 18 U.S.C. §§ 241 and 242 are "crimes of violence"); see also {{usc|42|1981|1985}}; ''[[Ziglar v. Abbasi]]'', {{ussc|582|___|2017}}; ''Lyttle v. United States'', [https://casetext.com/case/lyttle-v-united-states-3#p1269 867 F.Supp.2d 1256], 1270 ([[United States District Court for the Middle District of Georgia|M.D. Ga.]] 2012) (case about a U.S.-born citizen [[deportation|deported]] from the United States by the [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] "as an 'alien who is convicted of an aggravated felony.'").</ref><ref name="war crimes">{{USC|18|2441}} ("War crimes").</ref><ref name=Michels/><ref name=Lieu/> In other words, the lives of these [[wikt:vulnerable#English|vulnerable]] people should not be in the hands of a few judges,<ref name=Mejia>{{cite news|title=It's not just people in the U.S. illegally — ICE is nabbing lawful permanent residents too |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-lawful-resident-20180628-htmlstory.html |date=June 28, 2018 |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |editor=Brittny Mejia |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In a secretive court system with a huge backlog of immigration cases, ICE and others draw little accountability. |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/immigration-court-ice-police-arrests-bribes-racial-profiling-pro-publica-part-3.html |date=April 17, 2018 |work=Deborah Sontag and Dale Russakoff |publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]] |accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref> who often make serious [[reversible error]]s in [[removal proceedings|immigration-related cases]].<ref name="reversible errors">See, e.g., ''[[Trump v. Hawaii]]'', {{ussc|585|___|2018}} (Ninth Circuit reversed); ''[[Reyes Mata v. Lynch]]'', 576 U.S. ___, ___, [https://casetext.com/case/mata-v-lynch-1 135 S.Ct. 2150], 1253 (2015) (Fifth Circuit reversed); ''[[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 585|Pereira v. Sessions]]'', {{ussc|585|___}}, 138 S. Ct. 2105 (2018) ([https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/17pdf/17-459_1o13.pdf Slip Opinion, pp.7-8]) (reversing the 1st, 2nd, 4th, 6th, 7th, 9th and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|11th]] Circuits).</ref> An unknown number of these legal immigrants statutorily qualify as [[Americans]].<ref name=American/> The job of Congress is to equally protect everyone in the United States,<ref>''United States v. Maravilla'', [https://casetext.com/case/us-v-maravilla 907 F.2d 216] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|1st Cir.]] 1990) (addressing the pre-amended version of 18 U.S.C. § 242 in an immigration-related case that involved the kidnapping, robbing and [[Murder#Degrees of murder|cold-blooded murder]] of a visiting businessman by two U.S. immigration officers); {{usc|18|242}} ("Notes: 1994—.... Pub. L. 103–322, § 320201(b), substituted 'any person in any State' for 'any inhabitant of any State' and 'on account of such person' for 'on account of such inhabitant'....")</ref><ref name=Michels>{{cite news|title=Deportation blocked for Mexican national who settled Montana jailhouse rape claim |url=https://helenair.com/news/state-and-regional/deportation-blocked-for-mexican-national-who-settled-montana-jailhouse-rape/article_ccd01350-14a1-55a9-ae46-4969f4126d7d.html |date=August 2, 2017 |publisher=[[Independent Record]] |last=Michels |first=Holly |accessdate=2018-08-22}}</ref><ref name=Lieu>{{cite news|title=Former ICE agent arrested on sexual assault, rape charges, agency says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/08/19/former-ice-agent-arrested-on-sexual-assault-rape-charges-agency-says.html |date=August 19, 2018 |publisher=Fox News |editor=Amy Lieu |accessdate=2018-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former ICE Lawyer Who Stole Immigrants’ Identities Gets 4 Years in Prison |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/us/ice-seattle-immigrant-identities.html |date=June 28, 2018 |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |editor=Christine Hauser |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Federal Immigration Agent Stole Cash from Deportees, Nabbed in Sting: DA |url=https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/Federal-Agent-Faces-Charges-For-Stealing-From-Prisoner-Assigned-to-Protect-294824491.html |date=March 3, 2015 |publisher=[[WCAU]] |editor=Vince Lattanzio |accessdate=2018-07-23}}</ref> not only those who merely possess a simple paper showing U.S. citizenship. In many cases, such documents are [[forgery|forged]] and/or criminally obtained.<ref>{{cite web|title=Illegal Alien Convicted Of Passport Fraud, False Claim Of U.S. Citizenship And Aggravated Identity Theft |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ndia/pr/illegal-alien-convicted-passport-fraud-false-claim-us-citizenship-and-aggravated |date=August 14, 2013 |publisher=U.S. Dept. of Justice (DOJ) |accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Immigrant pleads guilty to using fake birth certificate to obtain a U.S. documents |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/immigration/article53897170.html |date=January 9, 2016 |first=Alfonso |last=Chardy |publisher=Miami Herald |accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Illegal immigrant from Mexico pleads guilty to using fake identity to steal $361,000 in government benefits |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/03/04/illegal-immigrant-from-mexico-pleads-guilty-to-using-fake-identity-to-steal-361000-in-government-benefits.html |date=March 4, 2018 |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref name=OPA/><ref>{{cite news|title=Trump Administration Denies Passports To Americans Living On Border: Report |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-administration-denies-passports-to-americans-living-on-border-report_us_5b87b403e4b0162f471fcc00 |date=August 30, 2018 |publisher=Huffpost |editor=Liza Hearon |accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref><ref>''Saliba v. Att’y Gen.'', [https://casetext.com/case/saliba-v-attorney-gen-of-us 828 F.3d 182] (3d Cir. 2016); ''Nesari v. Taylor'', [https://casetext.com/case/nesari-v-taylor 806 F. Supp. 2d 848] (E.D. Va. 2011)</ref> Congress instructed the courts by using [[plain language]] in § 1252(f)(2) ("[[Exceptional circumstances#United States|Particular cases]]") to apply a case-by-case analysis and ''de novo'' review.<ref name="injunctive relief"/><ref name="Nken v. Holder"/>

==Consequences of illegal re-entry after deportation==
{{Further|Waiver of inadmissibility (United States)}}
[[File:Border Patrol Vehicle near U.S. Mexico Border.jpg|thumb|[[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] on patrol near the [[San Diego–Tijuana|U.S.-Mexico]] border.]]
Every non-immigrant convicted of any aggravated felony and lawfully deported "must remain outside of the United States for twenty consecutive years from the deportation date before he or she is eligible to re-enter the United States."<ref>{{uscfr|8|1212.2}}</ref> That stringent rule, however, does not apply to legal immigrants who have been deported as aggravated felons.<ref name=a-f-1996>{{uscsub|8|1101|a|43}} ("<u>The term [aggravated felony] applies to an offense described in this paragraph</u> whether in violation of Federal or State law '''''and''''' applies to such an offense in violation of the law of a foreign country <u>for which the term of imprisonment was completed within the previous 15 years</u>.") (emphasis added); ''Matter of Vasquez-Muniz'', [https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/eoir/legacy/2014/07/25/3461.pdf 23 I&N Dec. 207], 211 (BIA 2002) (en banc) ("This penultimate sentence, governing the enumeration of crimes in section 101(a)(43) of the Act, refers the reader to ''all'' of the crimes 'described in' the aggravated  felony  provision."); ''[[Luna Torres v. Lynch]]'', 578 U.S. ___, [https://www.leagle.com/decision/insco20160519f95 136 S.Ct. 1623] (2016) ("So, putting aside the 15-year curlicue, the penultimate sentence provides that an offense listed in § 1101(a)(43) is an aggravated felony whether in violation of federal, state, or foreign law."); see also {{uscfr|8|1001.1}}(t) ("The term aggravated felony means a crime (or a conspiracy or attempt to commit a crime) described in section 101(a)(43) of the Act. '''This definition is applicable to any proceeding, application, custody determination, or [[adjudication]] pending on or <u>after September 30, 1996</u>''', but shall apply under section 276(b) of the Act only to violations of section 276(a) of the Act occurring on or after that date.") (emphasis added).</ref><ref name="Matter of J-H-J-"/><ref name="Matter of H-N-"/><ref name="reasonable interpretation"/><ref name="notwithstanding clause"/><ref name="statutory interpretation"/> An unknown number of previously removed aliens are residing inside the United States, some of whom have been removed from the United States about a dozen of times.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/07/15/illegal-immigrant-accused-attacking-wife-with-chainsaw-was-deported-11-times-officials-say.html |title=Illegal immigrant accused of attacking wife with chainsaw was deported 11 times, officials say |publisher=Fox News |editor=Katherine Lam |date=July 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/08/10/mexican-citizen-previously-deported-with-long-rap-sheet-arrested-in-us-for-10th-time.html |title=Mexican citizen previously deported with long rap sheet arrested in US for 10th time |publisher=Fox News |editor=Lucia I. Suarez Sang |date=August 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>

According to {{USC|8|1326}}, it is a federal [[crime]] for any non-criminal alien to illegally enter the United States after that alien has been denied entry, excluded, removed, deported, or if he or she has departed the United States while an order of removal was outstanding. The maximum sentence for this crime is 2 years of [[imprisonment]]. However, if he or she was a criminal alien and "whose removal was subsequent to a conviction for commission of three or more [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|misdemeanors]] involving drugs, crimes against the person, or both, or a [[classes of offenses under United States federal law|felony]] (other than an aggravated felony), such alien shall be fined under title 18, imprisoned not more than 10 years, or both."<ref>{{uscsub|8|1326|b|1}}</ref> 

The penalty can be increased to as high as 20 years of imprisonment in the case of an alien convicted for illegally reentering the United States after he or she was lawfully deported as an aggravated felon. Such penalty, however, is extremely rare since no alien has received that many years of imprisonment. Most defendants in such cases receive around 5 years of imprisonment. In ''[[Almendarez-Torres v. United States]]'', {{ussc|523|224|1998}}, the U.S. Supreme Court held that this increased maximum sentence did not violate the [[Sixth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Sixth Amendment]] to the U.S. Constitution. The only person saved from guilt and serving any imprisonment for illegal reentry after deportation is someone like the [[petitioner]] in ''United States v. Aguilera-Rios'', [https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-aguilera-rios-2#p629 769 F.3d 626], 628-29 (9th Cir. 2014), who "was not originally removable as charged, and so could not be convicted of illegal reentry."

